@d3 2
a4 1
\section{Characters in Adventurers Guild}
d6 21
a26 65
A player assumes the role of a character. The player develops the
personality of the character during adventures; the character's
needs, foibles, and ethos are revealed through interaction with the
other players' characters and the creatures represented by the GM.
The manner in which the character's personality develops will
undoubtedly be affected by that character's characteristics.  A
characteristic is a measure of a facet of the character's physical or
mental make-up which the player does not invent.

Characters begin play at an age such that their body has matured
enough that further growth will not alter their characteristics.  The
character does have some of their life already behind them; the
memories of those times must be supplied by the player, but any monies
and experience accumulated are the character's to spend.  Players are
encouraged to develop a history and a set of basic motivations for the
character.  These should be consistent with characteristic points,
skills, etc and the GM should insist that the persona and history of
the character be explainable in these terms.

A player must keep track of the statistical data (e.g.,
characteristics) concerning their character. The GM can choose to use
a different recording form, or modify the one provided.  Whichever the
case, the GM must be provided with a complete and current character
record for each player's character.  The GM can then verify the
information on each record, or make corrections where necessary.  Each
player should also have a copy of their own character's record, though
as play goes on, the two records will differ (the GM may note
something about a character which the player does not know, such as a
curse).  In addition to a character record, a player must maintain a
notebook for recording all monetary and EP expenditure.  This should
be checked by the GM at the beginning of every adventure and ``signed
off'' by the GM when satisfied that all calculations are correct with
respect to money, time and EP.

All characters must be rolled up with a GM present.  The GM's role is
to provide advice required as regards the rules, to counsel with
respect to choice of race, skills, etc. to suit the player's vision of
the character, and to verify dice rolls.  When the character is
completely rolled up the character must be interviewed by a member of
the Adventurers Guild Membership Tribunal, and sign the Guild
membership form before being accepted as a Guild member and can go
adventuring. This gives another GM an opportunity to check that the
character has been correctly rolled up and all aspects properly
considered.

\section{Description of Characteristics}

The player must generate and/or assign values to each of the
character's first eight characteristics, listed below.

The first six characteristics are the \emph{primary} characteristics.
Primary characteristics can be increased temporarily by magic or or
permanently by the expenditure of experience, and can be decreased
temporarily by magic or injury, or permanently by injury to the
character.  These primary characteristics can never be increased more
than 5 above their starting value by the expenditure of experience
points, and never above racial maximum, except by magical means.  All
other characteristics, whether or not optional, are \emph{secondary}
characteristics.  The manner in which a secondary characteristic can
be changed will be covered in the appropriate rule.  A ``temporary''
change indicates an increase or decrease of limited duration to the
value of a characteristic; a ``permanent'' change indicates an
increase or decrease of indefinite duration to the value of a
characteristic.  Adventurers in a world of magic can expect to be in a
state of flux for most of the time.
d30 1
a30 1
lack of such ability.  A characteristic's effect is almost always
d32 21
a52 1
during play.
d54 37
a90 25
Though characteristics are relatively fixed, a player retains total
freedom of choice for the character.  When a player shapes the
personality of the character, the player will probably wish to account
for some of the character's more extreme characteristics.  For
instance, if a character with an extremely low Physical Strength value
decided to specialise in magic, the character might compensate for an
inferiority complex developed during adolescence (due to constant
bullying) by choosing spells of destruction.  The spells would, or
course, allow that character to stand off the would-be Conans of the
world.  A character with a high value in Agility might indulge in
frivolous sports, because of a natural talent in such activities.
Remember, the greater the care taken when characterising, the more
``real'' the character becomes.  The player should strive for
consistency in developing facets of the character's emotional
make-up.

\subsection{Physical Strength (PS)}

\subsubsection{\emph{Physical Strength} is a measure of a character's
muscle co-ordination and strength.}

The Physical Strength characteristic represents the brute force a
character can exert from the thews of their arms, the thrusting power
of their leg muscles, and their lift and weight capacity (using leg,
back and stomach muscles).
d94 2
a95 4
\subsubsection{\emph{Manual Dexterity} is a measure of a character's
digital control.}

The Manual Dexterity characteristic represents the character's
d100 1
a100 1
\subsection{Agility (AG)}
d102 11
a112 2
\subsubsection{\emph{Agility} is a measure of a character's ability to
manoeuvre their body and their speed of movement.}
d114 2
a115 3
The Agility characteristic represents the character's litheness of
body, the speed at which the character can run, and their ability to
dodge with or contort their body.
d117 22
a138 1
\subsection{Endurance (EN)}
d140 2
a141 8
\subsubsection{\emph{Endurance} is a measure of the punishment a
character's body can absorb before the character becomes unconscious,
sustains mortal wounds, or dies.}

The Endurance characteristic represents the character's capacity to
withstand wounds, their resistance to disease and infection and their
rate of recovery from same, and directly affects their ability to
over exert themselves.
d145 18
a162 6
\subsubsection{\emph{Magic Aptitude} is a measure of a character's
ability to harness and direct magical energies.}

The Magic Aptitude characteristic represents the character's control
over the flow of \emph{mana} (the stuff of magic), and their ability
to remember spells and rituals.
d166 5
a170 6
\subsubsection{\emph{Willpower} is a measure of a character's control
of their mind and body especially in stressful situations.}

The Willpower characteristic represents a character's ability to
resist the imposition of another's will upon their own, the degree to
which their will can be used to counter their instincts (when, for
d172 1
a172 1
suicidal), and their ability to concentrate.
d174 1
a174 1
\subsection{Fatigue (FT)}
d176 12
a187 14
\subsubsection{\emph{Fatigue} is a measure of the length of time that a
character can sustain activities requiring a great deal of physical or
mental exertion.}

The Fatigue characteristic represents the number of potentially
serious wounds the character can turn into minor cuts and bruises by
their adroit or random manoeuvring in combat, the mental energy that can be
used to cast spells, and the degree to which the character can exert
themself before becoming exhausted.

The Fatigue value can be increased permanently, by expenditure of
Experience Points, and temporarily, by magic.  The maximum for a human
is 23, and for other races as modified by their racial modifiers.
This value may only be exceeded temporarily, and only by magic.
d189 1
a189 1
\subsection{Perception (PC)}
d191 19
a209 2
\subsubsection{\emph{Perception} is a measure of a character's
intuition developed as a result of their experience.}
d211 1
a211 5
The Perception characteristic represents the character's ability to
note peculiarities in a given situation (e.g. recognise an ambush),
their ability to deduce a person's habits or customs from scant
information, and their ability to gauge the fighting skill of
another person or monster.
d213 24
a236 7
The Perception value can be increased or decreased temporarily, as a
result of a character's performance during an expedition, and can be
increased permanently, through the expenditure of experience. The
maximum for a human is 25, and for other races as modified by their
racial modifiers.  Magic, certain natural or alchemical preparations,
and the character's condition can cause a temporary increase or
decrease in the Perception value.
d240 6
a245 17
\subsubsection{\emph{Physical Beauty} is a measure of a character's
exterior attractiveness (or repulsiveness) as perceived by a member
of a humanoid race.}

Physical Beauty is a characteristic representing a character's
appearance compared to the aesthetic standards of their society and
race.  A character with a high Physical Beauty value will be a
pleasing sight to a member of any of the races described in character
generation, though reactions will vary by race (for example, a female
halfling could find a male halfling with a Physical Beauty of 23
sexually stimulating, while a female human might think that same
halfling is extremely cute).  Physical Beauty is in no way a reflection
of a character's personality; a member of the opposite sex might
be smitten by a character with a high Physical Beauty value, but
the smitten character's subsequent reactions will probably be
governed by the beautiful character's personality.

d248 3
a250 38
This distinction is made because there is a greater incidence of
character-to-monster than monster-to-monster interaction, from the
perspective of the players.  Physical Beauty can be increased or
decreased temporarily by magic, and decreased permanently by
disfigurement. It cannot be increased by the expenditure of EP.

\section{Effects of Characteristics}

The characteristics do not cover every facet of a character's
performance on an adventure.  The GM relies upon characteristics only
when a player attempts a physical or magical action for which
character-GM interaction will no longer help decide the outcome.  If
the character must exercise their intelligence or wisdom (to name a
few facets of their personality not included in characteristics), the
player must provide the action or conversation for their character.

\subsubsection{If a character attempts a feasible task not specifically
explained in a rule, the GM derives a percentage chance of the
character succeeding.}

When a player declares that their character will attempt a task which
the GM acknowledges as dependent upon a particular characteristic, the
GM assigns the task a difficulty factor.  This difficulty factor will
be a number from one-half through to 5. The greater the difficulty
factor value, the easier a task will be to perform.

The GM multiplies the difficulty factor by the appropriate
characteristic, arriving at the percentage chance of the character
performing the task.  The player then rolls D100, and if the roll is
less than or equal to the percentage then the character has
successfully performed the task. If the roll is greater than the
percentage, but not greater than the percentage plus the relevant
characteristic, the character has failed without injury to themself
(if injury is at all possible).  If the roll is greater than the
percentage plus the relevant characteristic, then the character has
failed and may have injured themself.  The GM may wish to determine
the extent of the injury by how much the roll exceeds the percentage
plus the characteristic.
d252 1
a252 18
\begin{example}
Rolf the Barbarian informs the GM that he wishes to burst open a
solid-looking oaken door which has temporarily stymied the party.  He
proposes to use his trusty great axe to batter the door down.  The GM,
who knows that the door is buttressed by an iron bolt on the reverse
side, assigns it a difficulty of 2.5.  Rolf's Physical Strength is 20,
so if Rolf rolls a 50 or less (2.5 \x 20 = 50), the door bursts
asunder (and any traps will probably be set off).  If the roll is from
51 to 70 (2.5 \x 20 + 20 = 70), the door withstands Rolf's assault.
If the roll is 71 or greater, results will vary from the great axe
being damaged or broken to Rolf receiving a jarring shock (he hit the
iron bolt directly) to Rolf suffering Damage Points as oak splinters
penetrate his armour.  The result depends on the GM's discretion and
how great the roll is.  Rolf's maximum success chance is 70 + 20 + 2.5
(round down).  If the GM had assigned a difficulty factor of 5, giving
a Base Chance of 100 (5 \x 20), a roll of 96 or greater would still
have failed.
\end{example}
d254 3
a256 2
The following sample tasks are provided so that GMs can establish
their own guidelines.
d258 1
a258 1
\subsubsection{Physical Strength}
d260 3
a262 5
Opening doors and lifting heavy objects will be the two most common
tasks tied to Physical Strength.  Consider the sturdiness of the door
and the implement being used to open it for the former, and consider
the weight and bulk of the object plus the purchase afforded the
character for the latter.
d264 1
d266 5
a270 1
\subsubsection{Manual Dexterity}
d272 62
a333 102
Consider the delicacy of the task when a character seeks the careful
manipulation or removal of an object.


\subsubsection{Agility}

Consider the sturdiness of the structure being crossed or climbed and
the ease with which the character can balance themself when attempting
to cross or climb a poorly anchored structure.


\subsubsection{Endurance}

Consider how tired the character already is and how exhausting the
upcoming task if the character wishes to push their body to its
limits.

If more than one character is attempting a task which the GM will
resolve using these rules, the GM can reduce the difficulty factor if
their combined efforts surpass those of one.  If the task requires a
co-operative effort, the difficulty factor remains the same.  In either
case, the lowest-valued characteristic among the performing characters
is the multiplier.

\subsubsection{Magic tasks require the use of the Magic Aptitude
characteristic.}

In order to perform any activity involving magic (talent, spell,
ritual, minor magic or triggering invested magic), a character must be
a member of the class of beings that have Magic Aptitude.  In general,
the higher the value of the Magic Aptitude characteristic, the easier
it will be to perform the magical task.  Refer to Magic Book for more
detail.

\subsubsection{The information given the players by the GM will
sometimes depend upon a player's Perception characteristic.}

Characters will often have to rely upon their intuition and their
powers of observation at crucial junctures during an adventure.  The
GM can re-create a character's interpretation of events or of a
tableau in front of them by deriving a percentage chance (of the
character understanding the situation properly) from one character's
Perception value.

The GM should use this procedure to dictate what will be told to the
players only when the particular clue or piece of information is not
deducible from verbally-relayed data.  The GM should, for example,
inform the players that the ellipsoid symbol on the robes of the tall
man approaching them probably indicates that he is a priest, since the
circle is a religious symbol used throughout their world.

When the GM deems it appropriate to check a player's Perception before
answering a question, the GM either consults the Perception of the
leader or the character who is particularly suited to deduce
information in the current situation.  The obscurity of the
information sought determines the difficulty factor.  Multiply the
character's Perception value by the difficulty factor, and the player
rolls D100.

If the roll is equal to or less than the percentage chance, the GM
informs the appropriate player of that correct information.  If the
roll is greater than the percentage, but not greater than the
percentage plus the character's Perception value, the GM will either
inform the player that they are not sure or give them part (but not
all) of the information.  If the roll is greater than their percentage
plus the character's Perception value, the GM will mix fact with
fiction, the greater the roll, the more erroneous the information.


The GM should not avail themself of this procedure constantly during
an expedition.  It should be used when the players request more
information than the GM is willing to give them, when the characters
venture into foreign places or lands or meet alien people or races,
and when a decision is necessary to speed play.  Remember that
constant use of this procedure makes the outcome of the adventure
increasingly luck dependent.  A judicious GM will use the procedure no
more than once per hour (real time) during an expedition.

The GM will stint those players who constantly request use of the
Perception roll when it comes time for experience awards.  A player
who allows dice rolls to usurp the responsibilities of their mind
deserves no better.

\section{Generating a Character}

The player randomly generates their character's total Characteristic
Points.  The player assigns values, within specified limits, to each
of the primary characteristics from this point pool.  The secondary
characteristics are generated either randomly or as a direct function
of a primary characteristic, or they begin at a set number for all
characters.  Some of the characteristics will be modified if the
character is of a non-human race.  The player will not know the race
of their character (unless human) until all of the characteristics have
been generated.

The range of values for primary characteristics will normally be
between 5 and 25.  A value of 5 represents the minimum performance
possible by an adventuring character.  Thus, a character with a Manual
Dexterity of 5 could not effectively wield a weapon, but is not so
inept that they could not handle it without damaging themselves.  A
value of 25 represent the maximum performance which can be achieved by
a human.
d337 33
a369 10
\subsubsection{Each player begins the game with a randomly determined
number of Characteristic Points from which to assign values to their
character's primary characteristics.}

Each player may either roll 2D10 once and reads across the line on the
Point Generation Table corresponding to the two dice total, or elect
to have any roll up to 11 (81 -- 90 stat points), but if they choose
to roll the dice, they must accept the outcome.  The number of
Characteristic Points and Maximum value thereby obtained is noted on a
piece of scrap paper.
d371 1
a371 23
\begin{tabular}{ccc}
\multicolumn{3}{c}{\textbf{Characteristic}} \\
\textbf{Die Roll} & \textbf{Points} & \textbf{Max Value} \\
 2 & 81 & 25 \\
 3 & 82 & 25 \\
 4 & 83 & 24 \\
 5 & 84 & 24 \\
 6 & 85 & 24 \\
 7 & 86 & 23 \\
 8 & 87 & 23 \\
 9 & 88 & 23 \\
10 & 89 & 22 \\
11 & 90 & 22 \\
12 & 91 & 22 \\
13 & 92 & 21 \\
14 & 93 & 21 \\
15 & 94 & 21 \\
16 & 95 & 20 \\
17 & 96 & 20 \\
18 & 97 & 20 \\
19 & 98 & 19 \\
20 & 99 & 19 \\
\end{tabular}
d373 18
a390 26
\subsubsection{The minimum value that a player can assign to a primary
characteristic is 5, and the maximum value is set from the same dice
roll as above (before racial modifiers).}

Furthermore, a character can have only \emph{one} characteristic
equal to the maximum value, if that value is greater than 20.  The
character can have up to \emph{two} characteristics equal to the
maximum value if that value is 19 or 20.  In either case, the
character can have up to \emph{two} characteristics equal to \emph{one
less} than their maximum value and up to \emph{three} characteristics
equal to \emph{two less} than their maximum value.  If a character
does not have a characteristic equal to the maximum value, the player
can increase the limit of characteristics with a value one or two less
than the maximum value by \emph{one}.  Similarly, the player can
``transfer'' an extra characteristic equal to two less than the
maximum value for either or both of their two characteristics equal to
one less than the maximum value; thus, if it were mathematically
possible, a character could have \emph{six} characteristics equal to
\emph{two less} than the maximum value.

Prior to dividing up the characteristic points, the player should give
some thought to what kind of character the player wishes to have and
what weapons, spells, and/or skills desired for the newly created
individual.  Certain weapons require a great deal of Physical Strength
or Manual Dexterity and the player should be sure to allot enough
points in those areas to use the weapons of their choice.  All magical
d392 1
a392 1
should be aware of these restrictions.  Most Skills do not have any
d394 1
a394 7
value in certain characteristics.  The choice of race will also alter
the characteristic values, and the player must consider all
requirements and restrictions.

It is permissable to roll a character's Aspect (\S
\ref{chargen:aspects}) prior to the assigning of points to
characteristics.  Race must be determined after points are assigned.
d396 21
a416 20
\begin{example}
A player begins with 88 points (maximum 23) with which to assign
values to characteristics.  The player could choose a Physical
Strength of 23 (the maximum value), an Endurance and Willpower of 22
(the two with one less than the maximum value), an Agility and Manual
Dexterity of 9, and Magical Aptitude of 5.  If the player wishes,
the player could decrease their Physical Strength by one (to 22), and
increase either Agility, Manual Dexterity or Magical Aptitude by one.
\end{example}

When the player has chosen the values for the character, the player
writes them down on the Character Record.  The total value of the six
primary characteristics must equal the amount received from the Point
Generation Table; thus, a player cannot ``save'' Characteristic Points
and assign them to characteristics at a later date.  The value of each
of the six primary characteristics must be recorded before any
secondary characteristics are generated.

\subsubsection{The value of a character's Fatigue is a direct function
of their Endurance.}
a417 2
The player enters the Fatigue value corresponding to the character's
Endurance value after that EN has been modified for race.
d432 1
a432 1
Endurance and Fatigue values in boldface can be achieved only by
d435 28
a462 65
From this point on in the character generation process, a change in
the character's Endurance value will \emph{not} affect their Fatigue
value and \emph{vice-versa}.

\subsubsection{A character's Physical Beauty value is generated
randomly.}

The value of the Physical Beauty characteristic is generated by rolling
4D5 + 3.  A roll of 7 indicates an ugly character, while a 23
indicates a beautiful character.

\subsubsection{A character's Perception value begins at 5.}

\subsubsection{A character's Tactical Movement Rate (TMR) is a direct
function of their Agility.}

The Tactical Movement Rate is based on a character's modified Agility
value.  See the TMR (\S\ref{tables:tmr}) for values.

\section{Birthrights}

The worlds of \emph{DragonQuest} generally parallel the Europe of
medieval Earth, where women were largely relegated to secondary roles.
However, the bias is not as great in a fantasy world, for the
physically weak have recourse to magic.  Generally, a female
adventurer will be a determined soul, having surmounted cultural
handicaps.

A character's race is just as important as their gender, if not more
so.  In this world, a person's race connotes the colour of their skin.
In \emph{DragonQuest}, a character's race indicates that they are a
member of a distinct humanoid species.  Each race has a separate way
of life, developed over millennia of co-existence with one another.
Racial intolerance is common.

A good player will integrate the effects of gender, culture, and race
into the personality of their character.

\subsubsection{A player can choose the gender of their character.}

A character must be either male or female.  Every race described in
this section comprises only those two sexes.

Each player should choose the gender for the character.  It is
recommended each character be the same gender as the player. Role
playing a character whose entire gestalt is alien to the player is
hard enough without a change of gender.  If the player wishes a
character of the opposite sex, the GM should warn them of the
difficulties, and judge that player's characterisation as closely as
anyone else's.

As an optional rule, the Physical Strength of a female character is
decreased by \emph{two}, but her Manual Dexterity and Endurance are
increased by \emph{one}.  This would modify her appropriate racial
maximums.

\subsubsection{A player must determine whether their character's
Primary Hand is their right or their left.}

The player rolls D5 and D10.  If the D10 result is greater, the
character's primary hand is their right.  If the D5 result is higher,
the primary hand is the left.  If the two results are identical, the
character is ambidextrous.  This determination affects which hand a
weapon is held during combat, and any penalties assigned for attacking
with a weapon in a non primary hand.
d464 6
a469 13
\subsubsection{A player can always choose to be a human character.  If
the player wishes the character to be non-human, the player has three
attempts to roll within one of the indicated ranges.}

If the character is human, none of their characteristics are
modified.  The character gains no advantages and is subject to no
restrictions.

When the player wishes to have a non-human character, the player
declares which race they want the character to be, and roll D100.  If
the roll is equal to or less than the percentage chance given for that
race, the character is that race.  If the roll is greater than the
indicated percentage, the character must not be that race.
d473 1
a473 5
Dwarf		& 25 \\
Elf		& 30 \\
Giant		& 06 \\
Halfling	& 15 \\
Orc		& 20 \\
d477 10
a486 15
A player can attempt up to three rolls (for different races) to be a
non-human.  If the player fails on all three rolls, their character is
human.  Conversely, if one of their rolls falls within the indicated
span of numbers for a race, their character \emph{must} be of that
race.  A player can forfeit their right to any further rolls to be a
non-human if the player has exhausted the races the player wants to
be.

When a character gains proficiency in an ability, it is represented in
game by their player expending Experience Points. 

The cost, in terms of Experience Points, to advance in any one ability
is affected by the character's race.  In practice \emph{divide} any
experience points a character gains by the ``racial multiplier'' and
then spend the result normally.
d492 1
a492 1
Giant (hill)	& 1.5 \\
d499 4
d505 2
a506 2
\subsubsection{A dwarf is a stout, usually taciturn humanoid who
frequents mountainous areas.}
d508 17
a524 15
\textbf{Traits:}
Dwarves are enamoured of precious stones and metals, and of intricate
work incorporating same.  They form strong community ties, and are
distrustful of strangers, especially those of other races.  Their
strongest antipathies are towards orcs and elves.  Although dwarves
are greedy by nature, they are essentially honest.  Dwarven warriors
favour the axe as weapon.  Pride is important to dwarves.

\textbf{Special Abilities:}
\begin{enumerate}
\setlength\itemsep{0pt}
\item
A dwarf can see in the dark as a human does at dusk.  Their effective
range of vision in the dark is 50 feet under the open sky, 100 feet
inside man-made structures, and 150 feet inside caves and tunnels.
d533 2
a534 2
If a dwarf character is a Ranger specialising in caverns (spelunker),
they pay half the EP cost necessary to advance ranks.
d538 1
a538 1
\end{enumerate}
d553 1
a553 1
Starting Age: 20 to 24 \\
d559 1
a559 2
\subsubsection{An elf is a lithe humanoid, of joyful demeanour, who
frequents wooded areas.}
d561 20
a580 22
\textbf{Traits:}
Elves are great respecters of nature and learning.  They are virtually
immortal, and are at the same time, repositories of great wisdom and
highly enthusiastic merry makers.  Many elves cannot handle their dual
natures, and become either frivolous wastrels or grim questers.  The
elves are ethical by nature, and, although they do not often interfere
in the affairs of others, are traditionalists.  Elven warriors
favour bow weapons and disdain metal armour.  Members of other
races generally find elves attractive.

\textbf{Special Abilities:}
\begin{enumerate}
\setlength\itemsep{0pt}
\item
An elf can see in the dark as a human does on a cloudy day.  Their
effective range of vision in the dark is 150 feet under the open sky,
and 75 feet elsewhere.

\item
If an elf character takes the ranger skill and specialises in woods
environment, they pay one-half the Experience Points to progress in
ranks.
d592 2
a593 2
three-quarters the Experience Points to progress in ranks, though they
cannot resurrect the dead.
d599 3
a601 3
If an elf character takes the courtesan skill, the elf pays one-half
the Experience Point to process in ranks.
\end{enumerate}
