\section{Aspects}
\label{chargen:aspects}
d1005 18
a1022 6
The date and time of birth of a character will have a small, but
significant, effect upon the course of their life.  Some mana is
invested by one of the Great Powers into the soul, or life-force, of
every being born into a \emph{DragonQuest} world.  A character will
benefit during the time their Power is in full ascendancy, and will
suffer when the opposite Power is in full ascendancy.
d1025 1
a1025 1
applying the effects of aspects.  The GM should allow characters to
d1027 12
a1038 19
time must be properly monitored.  The GM may wish to counter the
players' timing with monsters and/or non-player characters who use
\emph{their} aspects to full advantage.

\subsubsection{Each player randomly determines the aspect of their
character.}

Each player rolls D100, and enters the result corresponding to their
dice-roll on their Character Record.

Seasonal aspects have an elemental portion.  If a character has an
aspect aligned with their college, then there is a bonus of 1\% on the
Base Chance of performing any Talent, Spell, or Ritual of their
college.  If of opposite alignment, then the modifier is -1\%.  Air
opposes Earth and Fire opposes Water.

If, on the first roll, the player rolls 91--00, then it is permissable
to re-roll until a roll of other than 91--00 is achieved.  Note,
however, that the first non 91--00 roll must stand.
d1064 1
d1066 15
a1080 9
\subsubsection{A character is affected by a seasonal aspect during the
season of their aspect and during the season which does not share an
equinox or solstice with the season of their aspect.}

Stars are ascendant during the season for which they are named.  The
Spring Stars are ascendant when the Autumn Stars are descendant, and
the Winter Stars are ascendant when the Summer Stars are descendant.
The reverse is true in both cases.  Consult the following table to
decide when to apply seasonal aspect effects, and what they are.
d1084 4
a1087 4
Midnight, Character's Stars Ascendant	& -10 \\
Midnight, Equinox or Solstice named for Character's Stars & -25 \\
Midnight, Character's Stars Descendant	& +10 \\
Midnight, Equinox or Solstice other than that named for Character's Stars & +25 \\
d1090 1
a1090 2
The effect is applied for 30 seconds before and after midnight, and is
applied to percentile rolls, not success chances.
d1092 1
a1092 5
\subsubsection{A character of solar or lunar aspect is affected by
their aspect at high noon and midnight.}

Consult the following table to determine when to apply solar aspect
effects, and what they are.
d1094 3
d1106 12
a1117 20
Multiply the solar aspect effect by -1 to determine the effect for
lunar aspected characters.  The effect is applied to any percentile
roll (not success chance) for a solar or lunar aspect character for 10
seconds before and after high noon or midnight.  If the sky is cloudy,
reduce the effect to a minimum of 1 and 5, respectively, depending on
how complete the cloud cover is.

\subsubsection{A character of life or death aspect is affected by a
birth or death in their immediate vicinity.}

Consult the following table to determine what events bring life or
death aspect effects into play, the range at which they effect a
character, and what they are.  For the purposes of life aspect effects
the moment of birth is considered to be parturition.

A life event is applied for 3 seconds times the range number (e.g.,
the birth of a humanoid mammal would cause an effect for 750 seconds).
A death event is applied for 1 second times the range number.  Death
events are non-cumulative (only one can be in effect at a given time),
though life events are cumulative.
a1118 2
A stillbirth does not affect a life or death aspected character.  A
resurrection is treated as a birth.
d1148 9
d1161 4
a1164 1
These effects apply to percentile rolls, not base chances.
d1166 1
a1166 1
\section{Heritage}
d1168 25
a1192 44
Most characters are of an age equal to one-fourth of their life-span
before players assume control of them.  A human character, for
instance, will begin with 18 of their 70 years already behind them.

The social position of the character's parents during the time of
their adolescence is described in general terms.

The heritage rules are designed with a human character in mind.  The
player of a non-human character and the GM determine the position of
the character's parents in the appropriate community by comparing it
to the human analogue given on one of the Heritage Tables.  The
experience and monies gained from these tables still hold, regardless
of this history the player and the GM sketch for the character.

\subsubsection{The player must determine the social status of their
character's parents.}

The player rolls D100, and reads across on the line corresponding to
the dice roll to derive the status of their parentage and their money
multiplier.

A character of noble birth will at all times have some sort of stigma
attached to them: they may be a natural black sheep or a remittance
person doing time until they will be forgiven for a disgraceful breach
of conduct.  In rare instances, a noble-born character will be
naturally adventurous; their family will probably dismiss their
departure from their proper station on some pretext or other.  The
young noble is certainly not performing the duties expected of them --
ruling the people in fief to them, or learning to do so.  A character
will never be of royal birth.

\subsubsection{Social Status Table}

\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{lXr}
\textbf{Die} & \textbf{Social Status}	& \textbf{$\times$} \\ 
01--09	& Poor Trash			& 2 \\
