d1301 4
a1304 2
\subsubsection{A player must determine their character's Language
Skills.}
d1306 4
a1309 51
Before they start adventuring, every beginning character must be able
to speak Common (not necessarily fluently) and read and write
somewhat.  If not a human or shapechanger, they will also always speak
their racial language (usually as their native tongue).  A beginning
character will have rank with all others languages in the same
language family.  They may be more fluent with these or other
languages depending upon their background.  For example, most Alusian
nautical terms are Espanol derived, therefore someone from a pirate
background might well speak at rank 2 or better.

Each character receives an initial allotment of language ranks
according to the table below that can be spent on language skills, 
and which is limited by the number of languages they may spend it on.
The languages and ranks should be justifiable within the framework of
the character's background.  They must allocate these as follows:
\begin{enumerate}
\setlength\itemsep{0pt}
\item
If human, then they must have Rank 8 in speaking Common.

\item
If non-human, then they must have rank 4 in speaking Common and
rank 8 in speaking their native tongue.

\item
If a magic user, then they must have rank 8 in their native tongue and
be literate in that language also.

\item
If literacy is required or chosen, the player must spend one of the
available ranks for each language the player wishes their character
to be literate in.

\item
Any remaining ranks may be spent according to the Language skill
rule.  This is optional, but any left over after allocation are
lost.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{Xcc}
\textbf{Social Status}	& \textbf{Number} & \textbf{Ranks} \\
Poor Trash		& 2 & 13 \\
Impoverished Gentlefolk	& 2 & 17 \\
Burgher/Farmer		& 2 & 15 \\
Merchant		& 4 & 25 \\
Merchant Prince		& 5 & 31 \\
Craftsman/Adventurer	& 3 & 21 \\
Bandit/Pirate		& 2 & 13 \\
Lesser Nobility		& 3 & 23 \\
Greater Nobility	& 4 & 27 \\
\end{tabularx}
