d252 14
a265 14
proposes to use his trusty great axe to batter the door down.  The
GM, who knows that the door is buttressed by an iron bolt on the
reverse side, assigns it a difficulty of 2.5.  Rolf's Physical
Strength is 20, so if Rolf rolls a 50 or less (2.5 \x 20 = 50), the
door bursts asunder (an any traps will probably be set off).  If the
roll is from 51 to 70 (2.5 \x 20 + 20 = 70), the door withstands
Rolf's assault.  If the roll is 71 or grater, results will vary from
the great axe being damaged or broken to Rolf receiving a jarring
shock (he hit the iron bolt directly) to Rolf suffering Damage Points
as oak splinters penetrate his armour.  The result depends on the GM's
discretion and how great the roll is.  Rolf's maximum success chance
is 70 + 20 + 2.5 (round down).  If the GM had assigned a difficulty
factor of 5, giving a Base Chance of 100 (5 \x 20), a roll of 96 or
greater would still have failed.
