The Tactical Movement Rate can be modified if the character is
non-human.  In addition, a character's normal Tactical Movement Rate
can be reduced if the character suffers an Agility penalty due to
wearing armour, or becomes encumbered due to the amount of weight
carried.
d527 2
a528 5
A character's genetic heritage will have a great influence upon them
throughout their adventures.  First, there is the matter of gender.

The worlds of \emph{DragonQuest} closely parallel the Europe of medieval
Earth, where women were largely relegated to secondary roles.
d532 11
a542 22
handicaps.  A character's race is just as important as their gender,
if not more so.  In this world, a person's race connotes the colour of
their skin.  In a fantasy world, a character's race indicates that
they are a member of a distinct humanoid species.  Each race has a
separate way of life, developed over millennia of coexistence with one
another.  Racial intolerance is just as prevalent in a fantasy world as
it is in this world.

Practically, each race has its strengths and weaknesses.  The human
race is the most prevalent, probably because of its high birth rate
and the flexibility of the individual human.  The elves, dwarves and
giants are races in their twilight years; human civilisation will not
treat them too kindly.  The halflings seem to be adaptable to almost
any way of life, and thrive because of their compatibility with
humans.  The orcs and shapechangers are nascent races, who may some
day challenge human hegemony.

A truly sophisticated player will integrate the effects of sex,
culture, and race into the personality of their character.  Most GMs,
while struggling to flesh out the cultures of their world, will settle
for the character who is the product of their racial and sexual
background.
d549 12
a560 10
Each player should choose the sex for the character.  It is recommended
each character be the same sex as the player. Role playing a character
whose entire gestalt is alien to the player is hard enough without a
change of sex.  If the player wishes a character of the opposite sex,
the GM should warn them of the difficulties, and judge that player's
characterisation as closely as anyone else's.

The Physical Strength of a female character is decreased by
\emph{two}, but her Manual Dexterity and Endurance are increased by
\emph{one}.  This also modifies the appropriate racial maximums.
